        "source":  "CIO.com",
        "url":  "https://www.cio.com/article/4197963/why-technology-leaders-are-losing-the-ai-conversation-to-the-people-who-report-to-them.html",
        "date":  "2026-07-17",
        "theme":  "Strategy",
        "summary":  "CIOs are being bypassed in critical AI strategy conversations by CEOs who seek confident answers from subordinates, vendors, and specialists instead. This occurs because CIOs traditionally lead with cautious risk assessments, which executives perceive as reluctance rather than prudent governance. Leaders who reversed this trend did so by developing confident, directional positions on AI while still addressing risks.",
        "execSummary":  "Senior technology leaders risk losing influence over AI direction not because they lack expertise, but because they communicate with excessive caution in rooms where confidence signals authority. CEOs are increasingly routing AI strategy conversations to more assertive voices ΓÇö vendors, specialist consultants, or direct reports ΓÇö creating a governance vacuum at the top. For enterprise leaders, the implication is clear: frame AI positions decisively and directionally, surfacing risk as a managed variable rather than a leading message. Failing to do so cedes strategic control of AI roadmaps to parties with less organizational accountability.",
